In an earlier era of rf/microwave testing, the measurement environment could almost always be assumed to be 50 ohms (or perhaps 75 ohms in the video-related world). Matching Electrochemical Impedance Spectroscopy (EIS) Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) is a powerful and accurate method for measuring corrosion rates. The corrosion rate at the monitored interface is proportional to the charge transfer resistance or polarization resistance.
